[5] Canada (Quebec) - all cases related
Date: Wed 11 Mar 2015
Source: CBC News, ex the Canadian Press [abridged & edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-measles-outbreak-grows-to-119-confirmed-cases-including-student-1.2990192


Up to 700 students and staff members are potentially at risk of contracting measles after a student attended the school while contagious. The elementary school has a pre-kindergarten program, meaning children as young as 4 attend the school. Public health officials in Quebec's Lanaudiere region said all of the 119 measles cases are tied to the outbreak at Disneyland. Three pavilions at the school are concerned: Wilfrid Gervais, St-Pierre and Marie-Charlotte.

The school says vaccinate or stay away. The protocol involves identifying all the unvaccinated people at the school and offering them the vaccine. 51 staff and 114 students were identified on Tuesday [10 Mar 2015] as not being fully vaccinated and health authorities began contacting them. All staff and students will have their vaccination records checked; information will be offered to parents, and vaccinations will be offered Thursday [12 Mar 2015]. Anyone who refuses to be vaccinated will be required to stay home for 2 weeks.

"I invite the people, the parents to make sure their children are vaccinated. It's a protection for their child, but for all the people around," said Public Health Minister Lucie Charlebois. However, Charlebois said that since 91 per cent of the region's general population is supposedly vaccinated, the school is better protected than the group affected by the outbreak.

Yesterday [10 Mar 2015], officials with the Lanaudiere public health department announced there were 80 confirmed cases of measles in the region. All of the people infected with the disease were unvaccinated.

The 1st Quebecers to contract measles were exposed while visiting Disneyland in California. Public health officials said Wednesday [11 Mar 2015] that all of the 119 cases are related. The confirmed cases are children or adults from the same religious community called L'esprit Saint, who were not vaccinated. A member of the L'esprit Saint religious community told the CBC that their prophet warns against vaccines, claiming they can lead to serious illnesses.

