[7] Canada (B.C. vaccine rejection)
Date: 9 Mar 2015
Source: The Vancouver Sun [abridged & edited]
http://www.vancouversun.com/health/Measles%20outbreak%20hasn%20swayed%20parents%20against%20vaccinations/10873789/story.html


Recent outbreaks of measles in North America have done little to change the minds of B.C. parents who've chosen not to have their children vaccinated, according to a new poll. The survey from Mainstreet Technologies, an Ontario-based research firm, found that 80 per cent of anti-vaccine parents in B.C. are "not at all likely" to vaccinate their children, despite the resurgence of measles this winter [2014-15].

"This is a continuing problem for those who cannot be vaccinated and depend on herd immunity for coverage," Mainstreet president Quito Maggi said in a press release.

Pollsters spoke to 1013 Canadian parents of children between the ages of one and 14 who have not been vaccinated against measles, mumps and rubella, and found that health concerns were the biggest factor in the decision not to vaccinate. 63 per cent of B.C. parents surveyed cited health concerns as a reason not to vaccinate, while 24 per cent pointed to religious reasons.

Education and income don't seem to play a big role in the vaccination decision, according to the pollsters. 39 per cent of anti-vaccination parents come from households earning more than USD 100 000 annually, and 38 per cent hold a university degree.

The survey was conducted by an interactive voice recording between 22-28 Feb 2015. The results have a margin of error of plus-or-minus 3.08, 19 times out of 20.

[Byline: Bethany Lindsay]

